SECTION A

1. (a) Multiple choice answers with explanations:

(i) B. Oral traditions — Oral traditions include stories and narrations passed from generation to generation, providing direct community recollections of the past. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

(ii) C. Africa — Early human remains and evidence of early humans (hominids) have been discovered in Africa, making it the cradle of humankind. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

(iii) C. It regulated European colonization of Africa — The Berlin Conference formalised the rules for European powers to partition Africa, leading to colonial rule. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

(iv) A. Industrial revolution — The need for raw materials and markets during the Industrial Revolution drove European expansion into Africa. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

(v) B. Desire for independence from colonial rule — Nationalism refers to efforts by Africans to end colonial domination and gain self‑rule. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}

(vi) C. South Africa — Apartheid was a system of racial segregation implemented in South Africa. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}

(vii) B. OAU — The Organisation of African Unity was established to promote solidarity among African states. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}

(viii) C. Kwame Nkrumah — Nkrumah led Ghana to independence from British rule in 1957. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

(ix) B. Development of cash crop economy — Colonial economic policies prioritised cash crops for export, shaping post‑colonial economies. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}

(x) D. All of the above — Many African states faced political, social, and economic challenges after independence. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}

1. (b) Matching:
(i) C — Pre‑colonial African economy existed before European domination. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
(ii) D — Colonial administrative system refers to systems of governance under colonial powers. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
(iii) B — Atlantic slave trade forced millions of Africans into slavery. :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}
(iv) E — Decolonization was the struggle for independence from colonial rule. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}
(v) A — Pan‑Africanism is the ideology advocating African unity. :contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}

SECTION B

2.
(a) History is the study of past events and human experiences over time. (Include reasons such as understanding the past to make informed decisions today, learning about cultural heritage.)
(b) Two reasons: to understand how societies change over time; to learn from past successes and failures.

3.
(a) Oral traditions preserve cultural practices, beliefs, and experiences of ancestors that are not recorded in written form.
(b) Limitation: They may change over time and be influenced by memory biases.

4.
(a) Two economic effects: introduction of cash crop farming that reduced subsistence agriculture; exploitation of resources for colonial benefits.
(b) Colonial education often aimed at producing clerks and labourers to serve colonial administration, creating limited access to quality education.

5.
(a) Causes of the scramble for Africa: Industrial revolution’s need for raw materials; European competition for global power; strategic locations for trade and military advantage.
(b) One consequence: artificial borders drawn at the Berlin Conference caused ethnic divisions and future conflicts.

SECTION C

6.
(a) Origins and development of nationalism in Ghana: Nationalist movements grew out of dissatisfaction with colonial rule, formation of groups like UGCC and CPP.
(b) Nationalism contributed to independence by mobilising mass support, strikes, boycotts and negotiation which led Britain to grant independence in 1957.

7.
(a) First World War exposed African soldiers to ideas of self‑determination; colonial powers weakened financially.
(b) Returning ex‑soldiers demanded rights and equality, inspiring nationalist movements.

8.
(a) OAU promoted unity by encouraging cooperation among African states and resisting colonial rule.
(b) Successes: helped end colonial rule in some states; Limitations: internal conflicts and lack of enforcement power.

9.
(a) Causes of political instability: ethnic rivalries, weak institutions, military coups.
(b) Measures to promote stability: strengthen democratic institutions; promote national unity education.
